						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">NESICIDE wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The difference here is that in that method the Execution Visualizer would show what your code is doing because your code is doing it [ie. turning on/off the tint bits].  In my example though the Execution Visualizer shows what your code is doing because you asked the IDE to show it to you</div>
<br />Which leads to a nice way to unify the two using the breakpoint system. A "tintpoint" would be like a breakpoint, but instead of stopping execution, it would set the tint bits when it triggers.
<br />
<br />EDIT: I thought of "soundpoints" too. These would be useful not only for debugging but also for making an All-Stars-style enhanced remake: mute the NES's sound and put a read soundpoint on each sound effect's data and each music sequence.</div>

