						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">NESICIDE wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">A "tintpoint" would be like a breakpoint, but instead of stopping execution, it would set the tint bits when it triggers.</div><br />Which, I *think*, is equivalent in most respects to the run-time interface via the IDE, which allows you to set a marked region of code -- aka "tintpoint" -- the only difference being the color used to represent the change of state.</div>
<br />Exactly, except the parallel with breakpoints might help people understand it better, and it would also allow setting color on events other than execution at a particular address. Breakpoint, tintpoint, soundpoint, logpoint, savepoint, scriptpoint, cedarpoint, it's just an idea for making your debugger engine more <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonality#Computer_science" class="postlink">orthogonal</a>. It separates the "when" (e.g. opcode fetch, read address, write address, write particular data at address) from the "what" (stop execution, set the color, play a sound, write the registers and a bit of text, save a state for later analysis, run a Lua script, ride a roller coaster).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

